sadoimpacto 2025-07-21 01:24 a.m.
To the issue of compensatory damages:

"The cardinal principle of damages in Anglo American law is that of compensation for the injury caused to plaintiff by defendant's breach of duty." 2 F. Harper & F. James, Law of Torts 25.1, p. 1299 (1956).

To that end, compensatory damages may include not only out-of-pocket loss and other monetary harms, but also such injuries as "impairment of reputation . . . personal humiliation, and mental anguish and suffering." Gertz v. Robert Welch, Inc., 418 U. S. 323, 418 U. S. 350 (1974). See also Carey v. Piphus, supra, at 435 U. S. 264 (mental and emotional distress constitute compensable injury in 1983 cases).

Even if there was no economic harm... the injury (being shot by a police officer) is still real and compensable, just not in the same amount that it would be in real life. To set a bare minimum floor...

In Rhoads v. Horvat, the court allowed a jury award of $5,000 in compensatory damages for an illegal arrest to stand, stating that it did "not doubt that the plaintiff was outraged by the arrest." 270 F. Supp. at 311. You've already said it is apparent his rights were violated (this goes to 3101.5), so the floor for a simple violation of rights alone would be, I'd say, $5,000. There also cases where for the deprivation of rights in regard to voting, substantial compensatory damages were awarded. See Carey v. Piphus, 435 n.22 U.S. 247 (1978) ("[Our cases] appear to support the award of substantial damages simply upon a showing that a plaintiff was wrongfully deprived of the right to vote.").

In those cases the reason damages varied so much is because the courts had a hard time discerning whether deprivation of abstract rights (voting, assembly, speech, etc.) could suffice as injury. They found that it did constitute some form of injury, but damages usually stayed between $25,000 - $100,000.

But here there is a real physical injury, as the Plaintiff was, of course, shot twice by a police officer. So the deprivation of his right to be free from excessive force is clearly traceable to an injury (being shot), that is substantially compensable. And then I think negligence, assault, battery... that's all pretty straightforward.

So I'd say...

Deprivation of Rights: $100,000 $500,000+
Negligence / Negligence Per Se: $150,000 $750,000+
Assault: $25,000 $150,000
Battery: $25,000 $100,000
Reasonable Compensatory Damages Range: $250,000 $750,000
Reasonable Punitive Damages Range: $500,000 $1,500,000
Total Demand: $1 million $2.25 million+

Some other case law you can read:
https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/435/247/
https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/477/299/

To the issue of compensatory damages: "The cardinal principle of damages in Anglo American law is that of compensation for the injury caused to plaintiff by defendant's breach o...
sadoimpacto 2025-07-22 02:29 a.m.
Punitive damages aside,[9] damages in tort cases are designed to provide "compensation for the injury caused to plaintiff by defendant's breach of duty." 2 F. Harper, F. James, & O. Gray, Law of Torts 25.1, p. 490 (2d ed. 1986) (emphasis in original), quoted in Carey v. Piphus, supra, at 255. See also Bivens v. Six Unknown Federal Narcotics Agents, 403 U. S. 388, 395, 397 (1971); id., at 408-409 (Harlan, 307*307 J., concurring in judgment). To that end, compensatory damages may include not only out-of-pocket loss and other monetary harms, but also such injuries as "impairment of reputation . . . , personal humiliation, and mental anguish and suffering." Gertz v. Robert Welch, Inc., 418 U. S. 323, 350 (1974). See also Carey v. Piphus, supra, at 264 (mental and emotional distress constitute compensable injury in 1983 cases). Deterrence is also an important purpose of this system, but it operates through the mechanism of damages that are Compensatory damages grounded in determinations of plaintiffs' actual losses. E. g., 4 Harper, James, & Gray, supra, 25.3 (discussing need for certainty in damages determinations); D. Dobbs, Law of Remedies 3.1, pp. 135-136 (1973). Congress adopted this common-law system of recovery when it established liability for "constitutional torts."[10] Consequently, "the basic purpose" of 1983 damages is "to compensate persons for injuries that are caused by the deprivation of constitutional rights." Carey v. Piphus, 435 U. S., at 254 (emphasis added). See also id., at 257 ("damages awards under 1983 should be governed by the principle of compensation").
